# Repository Documentation Structure Guide

This document defines a professional documentation structure for ROS2, robotics, embedded systems, and software repositories.

It can be reused as a template when creating new repositories.

This structure follows commonly used patterns from:

- ROS2 official packages
- Open Robotics repositories
- GitHub Engineering documentation
- Python Packaging Authority (PyPA)
- Google Developer Documentation Style Guide
- Microsoft Engineering Writing Guide

---

# 1️⃣ Project Title

```
# Project Name (Technology / Platform)
```

Clear and descriptive.

Example:
```
# IMU Serial Node (ROS 2 - Humble)
```

---

# 2️⃣ Short Description (2–3 lines)

Explain:

- What the project does
- What technology it uses
- What problem it solves

Example:
```
ROS 2 driver for Serial IMU sensor.
Publishes standard sensor_msgs/Imu messages for robotics applications.
```

Keep it concise and technical.

---

# 3️⃣ Overview

Explain:

- Purpose of the project
- Main functionality
- Target users
- Use cases

Bullet list format preferred.

---

# 4️⃣ Hardware / System Requirements

Include:

- Sensors used
- Communication protocol
- OS requirement
- ROS version
- Dependencies

Example sections:

```
## Hardware Used
## Software Requirements
## ROS Compatibility
```

---

# 5️⃣ Features

List major capabilities clearly:

- Data parsing
- Publishing format
- Configuration method
- Launch system
- Multi-device support
- Auto-detection
- Calibration
- Performance specs

Keep it clean and technical.

---

# 6️⃣ Installation

Always structured as:

### 1️⃣ Clone
### 2️⃣ Build
### 3️⃣ Source

Use proper code blocks:

```bash
git clone ...
colcon build
source install/setup.bash
```

Never mix explanation and commands in same line.

---

# 7️⃣ Configuration (If Applicable)

If the project uses:

- YAML
- JSON
- Config files
- Parameters

Explain:

- Where file is located
- Example configuration
- Parameter explanation

Always show example config in code block:

```yaml
parameter_name: value
```

Then explain each parameter clearly.

---

# 8️⃣ Usage / Running the Project

Separate section:

```
## Running the Driver
```

Example:

```bash
ros2 launch package_name launch_file.py
```

Then explain:

- What runs
- What topics are created
- What nodes are spawned

---

# 9️⃣ Published Topics / API

If ROS project:

```
## Published Topics
## Subscribed Topics
## Services
## Parameters
```

For software project:

```
## API Endpoints
## CLI Commands
```

This makes it industrial-grade.

---

# 🔟 Visualization / Output

If applicable:

- RViz instructions
- Web UI access
- Dashboard access
- Example output

Step-by-step format preferred.

---

# 1️⃣1️⃣ Package Structure

Always include directory tree:

```
project/
├── src/
├── launch/
├── config/
├── README.md
```

This helps new contributors understand architecture quickly.

---

# 1️⃣2️⃣ Troubleshooting

Common problems:

- Permission issues
- Dependency issues
- Port detection
- Build errors

Short, practical fixes only.

---

# 1️⃣3️⃣ Future Improvements (Optional)

- Planned features
- Scalability ideas
- Integration possibilities

Do not overpromise.

---

# 1️⃣4️⃣ Author Section

Include:

- Name
- Field
- Area of specialization
- Contact (optional)

Keep professional tone.

---

# 1️⃣5️⃣ License

Always clearly define:

```
© Year Name
All rights reserved.
```

Or open-source license (MIT, Apache, BSD).

Never leave license undefined.

